Pre-Experiment Design

Experiment Information

WLBR SIM link: https://sim.amazon.com/issues/WLBR-27897

Additional Helpful Links (optional / as applicable):
Project Documentation: Context-based index level synonym expansion  Context-based Missing Token Expansion NA Weblab
Related Experiments: Synonym expansion UK weblab deep dive Synonym expansion NA Weblab Summary Synonym expansion global launch summary

 

Objective

What are you trying to do? How do you think it will benefit shoppers, advertisers and/or Amazon? Which key segments will be impacted by this weblab (e.g. Prime, Books, Softlines, Top Spending Advertisers, Top X queries etc.)

Sponsored Products sourcing retrieves the relevant ASINs/ads based on users’ search queries. Solr achieves this by query tokens matching on the Solr inverted index. Sourcing needs to have high recall to ensure all relevant ads are returned and high precision to ensure high quality ads are selected with low latency. Currently, Solr improves recall by index enrichment. Synonym expansion for index is an established technique to improve sourcing recall. For example, when a user searches for “cheap lady watch”, ASINs which contain the word “woman” but not “lady” cannot be sourced. Using synonym expansion on ASIN title, we will add “lady” for these ASINs as a synonym of “woman”, allowing them to be sourced for this query.  Synonym expansion benefits shoppers by sourcing additional relevant sponsored products.  Synonym expansion benefits advertisers by providing impressions of Sponsored Products for relevant queries without forcing advertisers to explicitly include all synonyms in the ASIN title or description.  We also apply the same index expansion solution with ASIN attributes like product type and color; and user engaged/clicked query tokens that do no exist in ASIN index.

We have 2 experiment arms:

T2: (Synonym + Product type + Color + Engaged missing query token) expansion

T3: (Synonym + Product type + Color) expansions

What's Changing?

Spear team is testing the impact of adding a new data set generated from high precision context-based missing token expansion pipeline for building Solr Index on Sponsored Product Sourcing. Average 4 tokens were added for 18% of SP ASINs.  With the new data set, overall index match rate increased 10% in the offline match set which is generated from 1-day combined Organic and SP <query, all impression ASINs>.

We leverage a one-way synonym (<src, dest>: you can use "dest" to replace "src", or add "dest" when "src" exists) list mined by A9 and Spear team. There are two major sources:

  1. Synonym pairs from open sources like WordNet
  2. Candidate generation pipeline based on language modeling
    1. Generate token pairs using word alignment on <query, engaged ASIN titles>
    2. Calculate token pairs weights using token pair cooccurrence frequency and transition probability

In <src, dest>, "dest" is not limited to synonym, it also includes mis-spelling, translation, stemming, abbreviation, category. There are more than 1M pairs in the list, and the precision is < 20%.

Synonym is context dependent so synonym expansion on ASIN title directly would cause irrelevance. For example, consider the query “1.5 volt lr44”. If we expand “v” with the synonym “volt”, the very relevant ASIN B01GAS1O5U can be sourced. However, it is not generally true that we should expand “v” to “volt”. “v” can refer to the roman numeral “5”, a type of shirt, a part of a model identifier, or many other things. In offline, synonym expansion on ASIN title directly would add 100+ tokens per ASIN, it will cause big latency increase for our Solr system. Adding too many irrelevant tokens to ASINs introduces spurious matches and Solr just have a very simple ranking function which combines bid and tf/idf. The existing synonym list is too noisy and we need some systematic way to do selection and filtering. As we are the sourcing stage, we expect down stream components (ectr, relevance, rule-engine, auction) to guard relevance to some extent. That means, returning few irrelevant ASINs from sourcing is acceptable.

To tackle all above issues and increase the number of relevant sourced results we introduce context-based synonym expansion. We mine 1-year <query, top 100 impression ASINs> from combined Organic and SP search results. Context for an ASIN consists of all the previous year’s queries that have that ASIN as one of the top 100 results. Instead of expanding a synonym pair for all ASIN titles which contain the source word, we expand only those justified by actual queries.

We experimented the above solution for UK in 2022/10. 14-day APT showed 0.25% SP revenue gain and 0.25% click drop. From the deep dive, we draw below conclusions:

  1. Significant recall improvement with context-based synonym expansion: 8% ad-depth increase after Solr LBF (LBF is used to de-dupe and ensure ads diversity)
  2. Use Tommy <query, top ASINs> as context to add tokens for ASINs is a good way to ensure the better quality
  3. 40% of recall were driven by gender, color, common tokens, product type, number, stemming
  4. Some irrelevant ASINs were ranked at pos 1 despite relevant results still being sourced. The downstream can not handle irrelevant ASINs very well (product type mis-match, product attribute mis-match). We need to ensure high precision tokens and <query, ASIN> relevance check in Solr. However, it’s hard to control the quality/relevance with the aggressive solution in Solr

Based on all analysis and experiments, we extend our context-based synonym expansion to high precision context-based missing token expansion solution:

  1. We generate <ASIN, missing tokens in SP index> (SP refers to Sponsored Products) from Tommy <query, top 100 impression ASINs> and <ASIN, ad targeting clause expressions>. Organic and SP have different search stacks and may use different ASIN metadata and user behavioral data to build inverted index. In SP, we support automated targeting (AT) and manual targeting (MT). That means, we need to do <query, ASIN> match for automated targeting, <query, ASIN> and <query, ad targeting clause expression> matches for manual targeting. Use <query, top 100 impression ASINs> as context, we add ASIN title token synonym into ASIN index if it can bring <query, ASIN> matches. Content vetting is a step in the Solr pre-indexing process, where we vet out irrelevant ASIN and keyword pairs. Those pairs will not be served online. Content vetting is designed to ensure <ASIN, targeting clause keywords> relevance and reduce the index size. We use token overlap between the targeting clause keywords and the ASIN index to determine if we vet out a pair.  Use <ASIN, targeting clause keyword> as context, we add ASIN title token synonym into ASIN index if it can bring <ASIN, targeting clause keywords> matches. With expansion, we can index more ASIN ads and recall more relevant ads by given search queries
  2. Select and review top 10k synonym pairs (rank by the number of new matches it can bring). Do synonym expansion on ASIN Title to add the missing tokens to the ASIN index
  3. In the same way, do ASIN product type and color expansion to add the missing tokens to the ASIN index
  4. Add missing tokens to ASINs if they are highly relevant from user engagement data. From <query, ASIN, clicks, adds, purchases, consumes> data, we first get <ASIN, missing token, distinct_query_count, total_clicks, total_engagement>, then we calculate <ASIN, missing token, engagement score>. Add missing tokens to ASINs if engagement score > threshold

This experiment is for context-based missing token expansion on Solr index solution. The main goal is to increase sourcing recall and reduce irrelevant match using very little index space. More relevant ad ASINs will be exposed to shoppers without latency impact, it will benefit for shoppers, advertisers and Amazon.

Where will the experiment be run?

There are 4 experiments for this solution. After we launched NA (US+CA) experiment in Feb 2023, we are working on experiments for the global launch.

1. NA (US+CA): experimented in Jan, 2023. Launched in Feb, 2023

2. NA (MX+BR)

3. EU (UK+DE+FR+IT+IN+ES, AE+SE+NL+SA+TR+PL+BE+EG)

4. FE (JP+AU+SG)

Triggering

What are the Triggering Criteria?

The experiment will be triggered for all Amazon keyword search sessions.

Is the experiment customer or session randomized?

It's session randomized.

Is the experiment an Experiment Weblab? If it is a Launch Weblab, why?

It's experiment weblab.

Launch Criteria

1. NA (US+CA) experiment - launched

Gating weblab: https://weblab.amazon.com/wl/SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_250159
Control:Treatment = 80%:20%

Experiment weblab: https://weblab.amazon.com/wl/SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_536837
C:T1:T2:T3 = 25%:25%:25%:25%
C is prod, T1/T2/T3 are in weblab fleets. C has better ad cache hit rate (7%-10% higher). We use T1 as control experiment.

Usually, Solr weblabs are at 10% allocation. This experiment is at 5% allocation. (For this experiment, we first dialed up gating weblab (90% vs 10%) on 1/5/2023, and we planed to dial up the left parts the next day. On 1/6/2023, there was an HIE happened on Solr EU weblab because of weblab fleets under-scaled issue with the higher and un-predictable Solr Traffic. Based on the situation, we had 2 options: 1. scale up the weblab fleets, then we can collect APT starting next Tuesday. But Fenix NAWS migration dial up was planed soon and every Solr weblabs need to be dialed down before that. So we can not gather even 7-day APT. 2. Gating weblab with 80%:20%. At last, we went with gating weblab 80%:20%)

2. NA (MX+BR) experiment

Solr only supports 1 experiment slot with 2 arms for 14 days. As Solr experiment slots are very tight so that we combined this experiment with RAI (MX+BR). We used T2 for synonym experiment and T3 for RAI experiment.

A Peregrine weblab ran concurrently with a 50-50 split in Fenix traffic. Half directed to Solr (Gating weblab), and the other half to Peregrine (designed as a middle layer between Fenix and Solr). Peregrine exclusively connected to Solr prod. The Gating weblab received only 50% of traffic from Fenix. Please see details in the Wiki for Peregrine FE: https://w.amazon.com/bin/view/Weblab/BarRaiser/SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_627104 and WLBR SIM: https://issues.amazon.com/issues/WLBR-33866.

Im Summary:

  • Gating Weblab saw 50% of the Traffic from Fenix
  • Treatmet of Gating Weblab saw 20% of the Traffic from Fenix (0.5 * 0.4 [Gating T1])
  • Since Experiment weblab only saw 20% of the total Fenix Traffic. The apt numbers are being multiplied by a factor of 5 to get the precise annualized gain/loss.

We will launch the experiment if it satisfies Bayesian Launch Criteria and Guardrails:

For NA (US+CA), we launched T2 as it satisfies Bayesian Launch Criteria and Guardrails

For EU (DE+FR+ES+IN+IT+EG+SE), we will launch T2 if it satisfies Bayesian Launch Criteria and Guardrails

For FE (JP+AU), we will launch T3 if it satisfies Bayesian Launch Criteria and Guardrails

Launch criteria - Positive outcomes that the weblabs should achieve:

  • Prob(SP Revenue > 0) > 0.667
  • Prob(NetCP > 0) > 0.667

Guardrails - Flat metrics that are required to be maintained by every weblab. Ignore the following metrics for marketplaces where the data is unavailable:

  • Prob(SP Clicks > 0) > 0.33
  • Prob(GCCP > 0) > 0.33
  • Prob(OPS > -30MM) > 33%
  • Irrelevance rate as measure by manual audits should be <5% or <= Control IR for top 9 markets (US, CA, UK, DE, FR, IN, IT, ES, JP) in both mobile-top and desktop-top segments

Experiment Duration

14 days

Post-Experiment Analysis for NA (US+CA)

Launch Decision & Win Claim

The difference between T2 and T3 is that we added behavioral based tokens to T2. T2 has more SP Revenue and Click gains than T3. We plan to launch T2 in US and CA marketplaces by 2/10 with annualized Positive Net CP +$262.1MM, Positive SP Revenue +$234.6MM, Positive GCCP +$461.5M, Positive OPS +$356.8MM

Executive Summary

We have tested adding a new data set generated from high precision context-based missing token expansion pipeline in Solr index. SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_536837 is with a gating weblab SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_250159. The experiment runs for 14 days and all metrics meet launch criteria (see above Launch Criteria and below Best Reasons to Launch). We will launch this weblab T2 to production.

Best Reasons to Launch
Key Metrics Meet Launch Criteria and Guardrails

From covariate-adjusted APT, the experiment T2 satisfies Bayesian launch criteria and guardrails

  • Positive Annualized SP Revenue: +$224,580,115 (1.13%) with P(SP Revenue > 0) = 1 for US, +$10,057,665 (1.69%) with P(SP Revenue > 0) = 1 for CA
  • Positive Annualized Net CP: +$242,038,055 (0.47%) with P(Net CP > 0) = 1 for US, +$20,083,305 (1.17%) with P(Net CP > 0) = 0.996 for CA
  • Positive Annualized GCCP: +$453,728,460 (0.02%) with P(GCCP > 0) = 0.996 for US, +$7,752,790 (0.01%) with P(GCCP > 0) = 0.631 for CA
  • Positive Annualized OPS: +$250,565,325 (0.07%) with P(OPS > 0) = 0.765 for US, +$106,263,305 (0.66%) with P(OPS > 0) = 0.959 for CA
  • Positive Annualized Clicks: +87,138,505 (0.32%) with P(Clicks > 0) = 1 for US, +7,670,420 (0.58%) with P(Clicks > 0) = 0.985 for CA
  • Relevance Audit Results: US treatment irrelevance rate is 3.05% which is smaller than 5%. CA treatment irrelevance rate is 6.71% which is smaller than control 6.93%
More data points

Search engagement metrics indicate an overall positive shopper experience

  • Search click rate +0.06% with (Prob > 0%)=0.9854 for US, +0.02% with (Prob > 0%)=0.5906 for CA
  • Search reformulation rate: -0.11% with (Prob > 0%)=0.0033 for US, -0.27% with (Prob > 0%)=0.0306 for CA
  • Search abandonment: -0.01% with (Prob > 0%)=0.2862 for US
  • Sparse results rate: -0.35% with (Prob > 0%)=0.0501 for US

From 2-week WIT: ACTR and SP attributed OPS lifts show better shopper engagements and advertisers benefits

  • For US, SP ACTR +0.1415%. SP attributed OPS was on par. From Search, SP attributed OPS increased 0.16%
  • For CA, SP ACTR +0.1358%. SP attributed OPS increased 0.04%. From search, SP attributed OPS increased 0.42%
Best Reasons not to Launch

RoAS Decrease

From 2-week WIT, RoAS decreased (-1.12% for US, -2.35% for CA). The decreases were explained by the larger increase in SP Revenue relative to a smaller increase in ads attributed OPS. From US + CA 14-day APT, SP Revenue was driven by increased CPC (+0.84% for US, +1.38% for CA) and clicks (+0.32% for US, +0.58% for CA). Checked RoAS changes based on gl_product, some decreased and some increased. See details in section "Detailed Analysis - gl_product Cohorts Analysis" section. As we emphasize both SP Revenue and ads attributed OPS increase, and RoAS decrease depends on product type. In the future, we can optimize within specific product types.

Offline measurement

SolrTPS latency impact: While the sourcing latency in NA is within guardrails, there was an increase of p99(2-3ms) for US due to addition of tokens

Key Observations and Durable Learnings

  1. Behavioral based missing query token expansion plays the important role in Click increase. Synonym and behavioral token expansion play the important roles in SP revenue increase. The difference between T2 and T3 is that we added behavioral based tokens to T2. T2 has +0.32% click increases for US, +0.58% click increases for CA, while T3 has on par clicks for US and +0.14% click increases for CA
  2. SP Revenue increases are by both CPC and click increases. For US, CPC +0.84%, clicks +0.32%; For CA, CPC +1.31%, clicks +0.58%
  3. Synonym and ASIN attributes play the important roles in OPS increase. In T3, we only added synonyms and ASIN attributes tokens. T3 has $614MM OPS gains for US and CA while T2 has $356MM OPS gains
  4. Solr high precision solution is required. We experimented the context-based synonym only expansion for UK in 2022/10. 14-day APT showed 0.25% SP revenue gain and 0.25% click drop. From the deep dive, we found more ads were severed from Solr and the CTR drop was caused by worse relevance. The downstream can not filter out irrelevant <query, ASIN> and ad bid is an important factor in auction. We need to control results quality/relevance in Solr. However, our inverted index Solr has several limitations: Solr does not have a sophisticated ranking model, it is hard to control <query, ASIN> relevance. In Solr, we merge all data sets to compose an expression field for matching and they have the same weight. It makes index enrichment harder and harder. Adding too many tokens will cause latency regression and irrelevant matches. Token selection and filtering is critical for Solr high precision solution. Besides using <query, top 100 impressions>, <ASIN, ad targeting clause expression> as context, we also crawled wikidiff.com to select synonyms and human-labeled synonyms to ensure high precision
  5. Extend synonym to more token types. From UK experiment deep dive, we found 40% of newly sourced ASINs were driven by gender, color, common tokens, product type, number, stemming. In NA experiment, we add ASIN product type, color and user behavioral query tokens expansion. In the future, we will experiment more token types like number expansion 
  6. In order to predict Solr feature weblab performance, we set up an offline measurement pipeline - build match sets & measure match rate improvement. We use 1-day <query, all impression ASINs> from Amazon search results (Organic and SP) as a full set (ground truth). Join the full set with SP index to get the match set. We define a full match as all query tokens are matched in the ASIN index_tokens. After adding new tokens to ASINs, match rate analysis allow us to calculate over index match improvement From synonym UK, NA and some other Solr experiments, we found offline match rate improvement is aligned with weblab SP revenue lift if we can ensure high precision solution. We can use match sets to predict the trend, not the specific numbers as different features have different precisions.
    • This experiment T2: For US, match rate +11.11% and SP Revenue +1.13%; For CA, match rate +9.07% and SP Revenue +1.69%
    • This experiment T3: For US, match rate +0.91% and SP Revenue +0.16%; For CA, match rate +1.26% and SP Revenue +0.41%
    • RAI (Add ASIN attribute tokens based on product type and NLP models): For US, match rate +0.33% and SP Revenue +0.1%; For CA, match rate +0.37% and SP Revenue +0.52%
  7. SP Revenue increases are by both CPC and click increases. For US, CPC +0.84%, clicks +0.32%; For CA, CPC +1.31%, clicks +0.58%
  8. From shopper broadness analysis, the experiment performed better on queries with query_specificity<=5 from SP Revenue, OPS, ACTR perspectives. Will deep dive to explore more opportunities in queries with query_specificity > 5

Recommended Next Steps

  • As we have already built the high precision context-based missing token expansion pipeline and we see good gains on NA experiment, next we will extend this solution to other marketplaces
  • As this solution has very high precision and can be applied to any ASIN attributes, we will add missing token expansion for more types like age, number and gender
  • We will also do fine tuning on token truncation as currently we only keep top 30 tokens for each ASIN
  • We built a high precision synonym list and will apply it to Horus to relax close and broad match
  • Deep dive and improve gl_product with decreased ROAS
  • Deep dive and explore opportunities in queries with query_specificity > 5

Detailed Analysis

US Shopper Cohorts Analysis

  • query_revenue_decile breakdown: ACTR increases for all segments except query_revenue_decile_1 (-0.4%). OPS increases for Toros and Tail segments. The experiment has more impact on Torso and Tail segments
  • Widget breakdown
    • ACTR dropped: sp_atf, sp_phone_search_atf, sp_phoneapp_search_atf, sp_detail_thematic, sp_phone_detail, sp_phone_detail2, sp_phoneapp_detail, sp_phoneapp_detail2, sp_phoneapp_detail_thematic
    • ACTR increased: sp_atf_next, sp_phone_search_atf_next, sp_phoneapp_search_atf_next, sp_btf, sp_mtf, sp_phone_search_mtf, sp_phoneapp_search_mtf, sp_detail, sp_detail_2, sp_phone_search_thematic, sp_phone_search_thematic_btf, sp_phoneapp_search_thematic, sp_phoneapp_search_thematic_btf
  • ACTR is positive among all shoppers (prime and non-prime), genders, and customers (recognized or not recognized). ACTR is positive for recent customers (<= 1 year), users with tenure more than 1 year. Customers with average and high numbers of purchases have positive ACTR. Customers with ages 18-44 years have positive ACTR
  • Customers with ages 45-54 have negative ACTR -0.25% on the second week but positive ACTR +0.37% on the first week. Customers with ages 55-64 have negative ACTR (ACTR -0.45% and OPS +0.49% on the first week. ACTR -0.05% and OPS +0.22% on the second week ). As OPS increased for this segment, it’s not a concern
  • More details in US WIT Analysis

CA Shopper Cohorts Analysis

  • ACTR is positive among prime shoppers, high-frequency and institutional customers, recent customers, users with tenure less than 1 year or more than 5 years.
  • ACTR is negative among non-prime logged in users, low frequency customers, customers without recent purchases.
    • non-prime logged in users have negative ACTR but positive OPS (ACTR -0.15%, OPS +2.85% on the first week, ACTR -0.12%, OPS +3.7% on the second week). It’s not a concern
    • average_customer of low frequency purchase customers have negative ACTR but positive OPS (ACTR -0.06%, OPS +0.84% on the first week, ACTR -0.54%, OPS +0.13% on the second week). It’s not a concern
    • one_purchase_customer of low frequency purchase customers have negative ACTR (-1.86% on the first week, -1.09% on the second week). As one_purchase_customer makes up only 1.14% of sessions. It could be noise. It's not a concern
    • Customers without recent purchases have negative ACTR but positive OPS (Customers with [3months, 1year] recent purchases, ACTR -0.62%, OPS +4.61% on the first week, ACTR -0.36%, OPS +10.27% on the second week. Customers with [1year, 2years] recent purchases, ACTR -0.4%, OPS +33.33% on the first week, ACTR -8.21%, OPS +9.05% on the second week). As customers without recent purchases make up 10% of total sessions, it could be noise. Also OPS gained on these segments, it’s not a concern
  • More details in CA WIT Analysis

Post-Experiment Analysis for NA (MX+BR), EU, and FE

Launch Decision & Win Claim

The difference between T2 and T3 is that we chose the different thresholds to balance Solr precision and recall. We calculated token score by new matches it can bring. For T2, we selected the top 5% tokens, and for T3, we selected the top 15% tokens. T2 has higher precision and T3 has higher recall. We plan to launch T2 in EU (DE+FR+ES+IT+IN+SE+EG) marketplaces with annualized Positive Net CP +$42.686MM, Positive SP Revenue +$36.543MM, Positive GCCP +$36.597MM, Positive OPS +$22MM. We plan to launch T3 in FE (JP+AU) markets with annualized Positive Net CP +$19.398MM, Positive SP Revenue +$15.606MM, Positive GCCP +$12.082MM, Positive OPS +$97.827MM.

In total, we plan to launch 9 marketplaces with annualized Positive Net CP +$62MM, Positive SP Revenue +$52.15MM, Positive GCCP +$48.679MM, Positive OPS +$119.827MM.

Executive Summary

We have tested adding a new data set generated from high precision context-based missing token expansion pipeline in Solr index. SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_536837 is with a gating weblab SPONSORED_PRODUCTS_250159. The experiments run for 14 days and all metrics meet launch criteria (see above Launch Criteria and below Best Reasons to Launch). In addition, recall of new index against the 1-day organic+SP search results increased by (12.77% for DE, 11.29% for FR, 7.26% for IT, 5.79% for ES, 21% for IN, 9.03% for JP, 1.67% for AU, 2.04% for SE, 19% for EG). The new data set also increased SP-attributed OPS significantly by (0.52% for DE, 0.79% for FR, 0.12% for IT, 0.16% for ES, 0.64% for IN, 0.63% for JP, 0.98% for AU). We will launch FE (AU/JP, T3) and EU (DE/FR/ES/IT/IN/SE/EG, T2) to production.

Best Reasons not to Launch

1. We will not launch MX and SG for big SP-attributed OPS and RoAS regressions.

2. We will not launch UK, NL and AE markets for big OPS regression.

3. We will not launch MX, BR, SG, PL, TR and SA markets because they failed to pass relevance audit guardrails.

4. For some launchable markets (DE, FR, ES, IT, IN, AU, JP and EG, SE), RoAS decreased (-0.37% for AU, -0.36% for DE, -0.15% for ES, -0.78% for IT, -0.34% for IN). The decreases were explained by the larger increase in SP Revenue relative to a smaller increase in ads attributed OPS. Big revenue increases were driven by clicks (actr) increases and CPC increases.

Key Observations and Durable Learnings

1. We've created essential components for index enrichment as part of this project

  1. We created a behavioral context-based missing token expansion pipeline to enrich the Solr index by taking context into account. The pipeline determines the context for each ASIN based on its historical queries and targeting clause keywords, and adds tokens to the bag-of-words only if supported by the behavioral context.
  2. To allow easy comparison of different dataset candidates, and estimate online impact we developed a new offline analysis framework that builds match sets and measures match rate improvement. We found that offline match rate improvements have a high correlation with actual weblab gains as long as we ensure high-precision via the behavioral context checking. See more details here DU Learning Session - Build the truth: match sets

2. Lots of extra efforts and challenges for synonym expansion global launch due to market/language specific data.

a. We need to mine and review language specific synonym list.

We leverage a one-way synonym (<src, dest>: you can use "dest" to replace "src", or add "dest" when "src" exists) list. There are two major sources:

  1. Synonym pairs from open sources like WordNet
  2. Candidate generation pipeline based on language modeling
    1. Generate token pairs using word alignment on <query, engaged ASIN titles>
    2. Calculate token pairs weights using token pair cooccurrence frequency and transition probability

For example, for English, there are more than 1 million pairs in the list, and the precision is < 20%. For Japanese, there are several million pairs.Synonym is context dependent so synonym expansion on ASIN title directly would cause irrelevance. We need high precision context-based expansion solution. For top languages, we select and review top 10k synonym pairs (rank by the number of new matches it can bring). 

b. We need to support "skipping tokenization" in prod.
As our tokenizer is not idempotent for some languages (MX, BR, DE, JP, ...), applying tokenizer on the tokens for different times will generate different tokens. For solr index enrichment projects, we prepare <ASIN, tokens> data sets offline. If we have already applied tokenization offline, we need to skip tokenization online. We need to support "skipping tokenization" in prod.

c. We need to remove bad expansions for different languages.
We remove common but irrelevant tokens for ASINs. Different languages have different patterns. For example, we remove 1 character token, common tokens like "Amazon", "best", some attributes like color from the clicked queries for English markets.

3. Launching in small markets is challenging

a. We need better experimentation design

Small markets have very little traffic, assigning 5%-10% traffic for experiments introduces noises and metric variance. Investing extensive efforts without launching is a waste of resources. We need better experimentation design: more traffic to small markets and gradual roll out experiments.

b. Downstream components perform badly on small markets. Extra work to balance precision and recall in Sourcing
The most important metric for sourcing is recall. We have the assumption that downstream (filtering & ranking & auction) can help some with the precision. From the relevance audit results, TOP 9 markets prod (SP impression) p-irrel are within 5%, Non-TOP 9 small markets, prod irrelevance rates are very high. For example, SG irrelevance rate can be as high as 20%. Synonym expansion experiments on 21 markets also show that TOP 9 markets passed relevance audit guardrails, but most of non-TOP 9 small markets failed relevance audit guardrails. That indicates the downstream can not handle irrelevant cases well. If sourcing returned irrelevant cases with high bid, these ASINs will be ranked high. We have a deep dive on UK experiment, there are many irrelevant ASINs were ranked high. For non-top markets, this issue is severe.

Pre-auction

  • Use rules_engine to filter ASINs with high p_irrel & low ectr (above/below thresholds)
  • GLO (global limit optimizer): NA rank ASINs by bid*ectr, EU rank ASINs by bid. Pass top 1000 ASINs to auction

Auction

  • final_bid = unadjusted_bid * eCVR / targeting_CVR
  • Ranking function

4. Global launch and post analysis (bar raising preparation) are very time-consuming

After launching in the US and Canada, we have 19 more markets. Each market requires language-specific tokenization, synonym mining, and a scalable data pipeline capable of adapting to market-specific parameters across all markets. This data preparation and validation required 1.5 months. Additionally, we also need to schedule weblabs for each region (3 in total), which adds another 1.5 months. After experimentation, we must complete the bar raising process, including sampling manually in each market and a human audit of 19 * 8,000 <query, ASIN> pairs (1 month ~ 2 months), generating all APT reports (2 weeks) and performing shopper cohort analysis (2 weeks). Furthermore, if there is any negative metrics in any market, deep dive and iterations are needed. In small markets, all experiments we run have negative metrics in some markets. In total, to launch this Solr weblab in 19 markets successfully would be expected to take 5 months development, weblab and bar raising time.

There are so many manual work and some measurements are noisy. For example, for AU T3 mobile data set relevance audit, the irrelevance rate is 9.8%. With the post-curation, the irrelevance rate is 8.07%. It's 20% variance.

5. OPS and SP-attributed OPS analysis

We categorize the current 21 markets that SP supports into three tiers based on market size and investment till date:

  • Tier 1: US
  • Tier 2 (8 Markets): EU 5 (UK, ES, DE, FR, IT) + IN + JP + CA
  • Tier 3 (12 Markets): Rest of the world (MX, BR, SE, NL, TR, AE, SA, PL, BE, AU, SG, EG).

The traffic in tier 3 markets are very low, resulting in significant fluctuations in metrics and affecting the overall decision-making process for shipping. OPS is Amazon wide ops during the experiments. Users may purchase the items added in the chart before they were allocated to the experiment. In general, OPS is very noisy. In EU experiment, C and T1 are both baseline (same code and data, C has higher cache rate), OPS of C is much less than T1.

For SP-attributed OPS, all markets except MX and SG have positive numbers.

6. Shopper cohorts analysis

a. For ach_prime_status, majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR, except (FR, not logged in), (IN, not prime), (NL, not prime), (SE, not prime), (SG, not prime). 

b. For is_recognized_customer, majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR, expect (FR, is_not_recognized_customer), (SE, is_recognized_customer).

c. For shopper_lifecycle_segment, majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR, expect (ES, unknown), (FR, unknown), (AE, unknown), (NL, frequent-prime), (PL, unknown), (SA, unknown).

d. For shopper_purchase_frequency, majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR, expect (ES, unknown), (FR, unknown), (IN, average_customer), (AE, unknown), (PL, unknown), (PL, high_purchase_customer), (SE, unknown), (SE, average_customer), (SG, unknown).

e. For shopper_purchase_recency, majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR, expect (ES, unknown), (FR, unknown), (IN, >three_monthsAND<=one_year), (AE, unknown), (PL, unknown), (SE, unknown), (SG, unknown)

f. For shopper_tenure, majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR, expect (ES, unknown), (FR, unknown), (IN, >two_yearsAND<=five_years), (UK, >two_yearsAND<=five_years), (AE, unknown), (PL, unknown), (PL, >two_yearsAND<=five_years), (SE, unknown), (SE, <=one_year), (SG, unknown)

From shopper cohort analysis, unknown segments on ES, FR, SE, SG, PL and AE have negative ACTR and ACVR. User behavior data play the key role in sourcing and down stream relevance, ectr and auction. User behavior data in unknown segment is less robust in small marketplaces due to much smaller population and fewer interactions.

7. Advertiser Cohort Analysis

Majority segments have positive ACTR and ACVR

a. For is_advertiser_partner_managed, only (IN, managed) has negative ACTR and ACVR

b. For advertiser_team_type, only (DE, LCS) and (JP, LCS) have negative ACTR and ACVR

c. For advertiser_type, only (IN, vendor) and (JP, vendor) have negative ACTR and ACVR

Recommended Next Steps

  1. Better experimentation design: Assign 5%-10% traffic to small markets will bring noises and launch difficulties. To reduce the variance in metrics, allocate more traffic for experiments. We can gradually roll out the experiments.
  2. We need unified efforts for small markets: Currently, relevance audit is the blocker for some small markets. Without downstream relevance, ectr and auction team's unified efforts, sourcing improvements on these small markets would be inefficient and slow. Given the high priority of global launches in SP, it's imperative to drive enhancements across all components. In the short term, we should devise an efficient solution to expedite launches and improvements. For example, we can launch these small markets if the relevance audit is the only blocker and then have a unified effort to improve relevance later.
  3. Simply the post analysis process
    1. Proposals to speed up relevance audit process
    2. Have dedicated effort to streamline the post analysis: shopper/advertiser cohort analysis and relevance audit.
